ur Lady in Old St. Peter's; moved to the sudarium on September 5, 1606 during the demolition.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|{{anchor|1500\u20131600}}1503\u20131503\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| [[File:Pius III, Nordisk familjebok.png|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Pius III|Pius III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Sebastiano Ferrucci]]. Originally built in Old Saint Peter's; last papal mausoleum erected in Old St. Peter's; moved to Sant'Andrea della Valle during the reign of Paul V.<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 177.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1523\u20131534\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Clement VII. Sebastiano del Piombo. c.1531..jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Originally buried in a brick tomb in Old Saint Peter's; current tomb is across from that of Leo X, another Medici pope in Santa Maria sopra Minerva<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 182.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1534\u20131549\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Tizian 083b.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Paul III|Paul III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Guglielmo della Porta]]. Moved in 1599.<ref>Reardon, 2004, pp. 185\u2013186.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1550\u20131555\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Julius III.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Julius III|Julius III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Originally buried in St. Peter's Basilica ''sans'' monument in a red stone sarcophagus in the chapel of San Andrea; reinterred in an ancient sarcophagus in 1608, which was reopened two years later during the demolition;<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 186.</ref> sometimes cited as buried in the Del Monte chapel of [[San Pietro in Montorio]] along with his adopted [[cardinal-nephew]], [[Innocenzo Ciocchi Del Monte]]<ref>Aldrich, Robert, and Wotherspoon, Garry. (2000). ''Who's Who in Gay and Lesbian History from Antiquity to World War II''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-415-25369-7}}. p. 278.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1555\u20131555\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Pope Marcellus II.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Marcellus II|Marcellus II]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|No monument; fourth century sarcophagus, bearing a ''[[Christ in Majesty|traditio legis]]''<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 187\u2013188.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1572\u20131585\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Gregory XIII.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Gregory XIII|Gregory XIII]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Original monument destroyed; new monument built in eighteenth century<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 195.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1590\u20131591\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Gregory XIV.PNG|70px|]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Gregory XIV|Gregory XIV]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Prospero Antichi]].<ref name=autogenerated1>Reardon, 2004, p. 199.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1591\u20131591\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Innocent9.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Innocent IX|Innocent IX]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|No monument<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Index of Vatican City-related articles]]\n* [[Papal tombs]]\n* [[St. Peter's tomb]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{citation | last = Gardner | first = Julian | title = The Tomb and the Tiara | publisher = Clarendon Press | location = Oxford | year = 1992 | isbn = 978-0-19-817510-0 }}\n* {{citation | last =  Mann| first = H. K. | year = 2003| title =Tombs and Portraits of the Popes of the Middle Ages| publisher =Kessinger Publishing| isbn = 978-0-7661-2903-0}}\n* Reardon, Wendy J. 2004. ''The Deaths of the Popes''. Macfarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1527-4}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|de}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100127105000/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/requiem/ Information and images on papal tombs (1417 and 1799)] from the Requiem project\n\n{{Vatican City topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|41.9022|N|12.4533|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter's Basilica|Old Saint Peters]]\n[[Category:Papal tombs]]\n[[Category:History of the papacy]]\n[[Category:Sarcophagi]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Grimaldi sketch.jpg|thumb|right|A sketch by Giacomo Grimaldi of the interior of St. Peter's during its reconstruction, showing the temporary placement of some of the tombs|alt=A drawing of the interior of St. Peters]]\nThe '''papal tombs in old St. Peter's Basilica''' were the final resting places of the [[pope]]s, most which dated from the fifth to sixteenth centuries. The majority of these tombs were destroyed during the sixteenth through seventeenth century demolition of [[old St. Peter's Basilica]], except for one which was destroyed during the [[Arab raid against Rome|Saracen Sack of the church]] in 846. The remainder were transferred in part to new [[St. Peter's Basilica]], which stands on the site of the original basilica, and a handful of other [[churches of Rome]].\n\n==History==\nAlong with the repeated translations from the ancient [[catacombs of Rome]] and two fourteenth century fires in the [[Archbasilica of Saint John Lateran]], the rebuilding of St. Peter's is responsible for the destruction of approximately half of all [[List of extant papal tombs|papal tombs]]. As a result, [[Donato Bramante]], the chief architect of modern St. Peter's Basilica, has been remembered as \"''Mastro Ruinante''\".\n\nAlthough the original basilica's construction was begun during the reign of emperor [[Constantine I]] and completed in the fourth century, [[Pope Leo I]] (440\u2013461) was the first pope buried in the Constantian basilica.<ref name=\"rear40\">Reardon, 2004, p. 40.</ref> Over the centuries, both the atrium, chapels, and the nave of the basilica were packed with papal tombs, which were juggled between different sections of the church as construction took place on each section of the basilica. All that remains of the original tombs are a few sarcophagi and sculptural fragments.<ref name=\"r272\">Reardon, 2004, p. 272.</ref> Allegedly, [[Pope Julius II]], the pope who initiated the destruction of the Constantinian basilica, wished to clear space for a \"monstrous\" tomb of his own by [[Michelangelo]].<ref name=\"r274\">Reardon, 2004, p. 274.</ref>\n\nVery little is known about the placement and appearance of the original tombs: one of the most valuable accounts is that of church canon and historian [[Giacomo Grimaldi]] (a senator of Genoa and the father of [[Girolamo Grimaldi-Cavalleroni]]), who sketched the tombs as they were moved around the basilica on the way to their destruction;<ref>Grimaldi, Giacomo. Ed. R. Niggl. 1972. ''Descrizione della Basilica Antica di S. Pietro in Vaticano: Codice Barberini Latino 2733''. Vatican City.</ref> Grimaldi's sketches record the shape and complexity of the early tombs, many of which were three-tiered.<ref name=\"r272\"/> A few destroyed papal tombs are also detailed in the writings of [[Alphonsus Ciacconius]].<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 12.</ref>\n\nNot all popes were buried in Rome. ''See [[list of non-extant papal tombs]]''\n\n==Papal tombs==\n{| id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\" summary=\"Class\"\n! {{MediaWiki:Toc}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[#400\u2013500|400\u2013500]]{{\u00b7}}[[#500\u2013600|500\u2013600]]{{\u00b7}}[[#600\u2013700|600\u2013700]]{{\u00b7}}[[#700\u2013800|700\u2013800]]{{\u00b7}}[[#800\u2013900|800\u2013900]]{{\u00b7}}[[#900\u20131000|900\u20131000]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1000\u20131100|1000\u20131100]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1100\u20131200|1100\u20131200]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1200\u20131300|1200\u20131300]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1300\u20131400|1300\u20131400]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1400\u20131500|1400\u20131500]]{{\u00b7}}[[#1500\u20131600|1500\u20131600]]\n|}\n:''Partially extant, moved, or rebuilt tombs are shown with a darkened background''.\n[[File:Alfarano map.jpg|thumb|right|A map, circa 1590, by [[Tiberio Alfarano]] of the interior of Old Saint Peter's, noting the locations of the original chapels and tombs.<ref name=\"r274\"/>|alt=A map of the interior of Old St. Peter's]]\n[[File:Expuls\u00e3o de \u00e1tila.jpg|thumb|right|Algardi's ''Fuga d'Attila'', above the altar containing the translated remains of Pope Leo I, \"the Great\"|alt=A photo of Algardi's ''Fuga d'Attila'']]\n[[File:Tomb of pope Gregorius I.jpg|thumb|right|The altar above the translated remains of Pope Gregory I, \"the Great\"|alt=A photo of an altar]]\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Tomb of Popes Leo II III IV.jpg|thumb|right|The combined remains of Popes Leo I, II, III, and IV|alt=A photo of the marble container of Popes Leo I, II, III, and IV's remains]] -->\n[[File:Archive plan for the original Tomb of Pope Leo III.jpg|thumb|right|A drawing of the original tomb of Pope Leo III|alt=A drawing of the tomb of Pope Leo II]]\n[[File:Atrium of Old Saint Peter.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Atrium (architecture)|atrium]] of Old St. Peter's Basilica, a popular site for tombs|alt=A drawing of the atrium of Old St. Peter's]]\n[[File:De sacris aedificiis a Costantino Magno constructis synopsis historica pag. 56 Tab. XV.jpg|thumb|Drawing of papal tombs, from ''De sacris aedificiis...'' by [[Giovanni Ciampini]] (1693)]]\n[[File:De sacris aedificiis a Costantino Magno constructis synopsis historica pag. 57 Tab. XVI.jpg|thumb|Drawing of papal tombs]]\n[[File:De sacris aedificiis a Costantino Magno constructis synopsis historica pag. 57 Tab. XVII.jpg|thumb|Drawing of papal tombs]]\n[[File:De sacris aedificiis a Costantino Magno constructis synopsis historica pag. 59 Tab. XIX.jpg|thumb|Drawing 