 in 1625 to the Chapel del Coro in new Saint Peter's; combined with Julius II in 1926; moved again in 1940s.<ref name=autogenerated2>Reardon, 2004, p. 167.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1484\u20131492\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| [[File:Innocent VIII.JPG|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Innocent VIII|Innocent VIII]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Antonio del Pollaiolo]]. First papal tomb to depict a live pope rather than a deathbed effigy; originally placed in the Oratory of Our Lady in Old St. Peter's; moved to the sudarium on September 5, 1606 during the demolition.<ref name=autogenerated2 />\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|{{anchor|1500\u20131600}}1503\u20131503\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| [[File:Pius III, Nordisk familjebok.png|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Pius III|Pius III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Sebastiano Ferrucci]]. Originally built in Old Saint Peter's; last papal mausoleum erected in Old St. Peter's; moved to Sant'Andrea della Valle during the reign of Paul V.<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 177.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1523\u20131534\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Clement VII. Sebastiano del Piombo. c.1531..jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Clement VII|Clement VII]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Originally buried in a brick tomb in Old Saint Peter's; current tomb is across from that of Leo X, another Medici pope in Santa Maria sopra Minerva<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 182.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1534\u20131549\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Tizian 083b.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Paul III|Paul III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Guglielmo della Porta]]. Moved in 1599.<ref>Reardon, 2004, pp. 185\u2013186.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1550\u20131555\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Julius III.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Julius III|Julius III]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Originally buried in St. Peter's Basilica ''sans'' monument in a red stone sarcophagus in the chapel of San Andrea; reinterred in an ancient sarcophagus in 1608, which was reopened two years later during the demolition;<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 186.</ref> sometimes cited as buried in the Del Monte chapel of [[San Pietro in Montorio]] along with his adopted [[cardinal-nephew]], [[Innocenzo Ciocchi Del Monte]]<ref>Aldrich, Robert, and Wotherspoon, Garry. (2000). ''Who's Who in Gay and Lesbian History from Antiquity to World War II''. Routledge. {{ISBN|978-0-415-25369-7}}. p. 278.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1555\u20131555\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Pope Marcellus II.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Marcellus II|Marcellus II]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|No monument; fourth century sarcophagus, bearing a ''[[Christ in Majesty|traditio legis]]''<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 187\u2013188.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1572\u20131585\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Gregory XIII.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Gregory XIII|Gregory XIII]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Original monument destroyed; new monument built in eighteenth century<ref>Reardon, 2004, p. 195.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1590\u20131591\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Gregory XIV.PNG|70px|]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Gregory XIV|Gregory XIV]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|Sculpted by [[Prospero Antichi]].<ref name=autogenerated1>Reardon, 2004, p. 199.</ref>\n|- valign=\"top\"\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| 1591\u20131591\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|[[File:Innocent9.jpg|70px]]\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"| '''[[Pope Innocent IX|Innocent IX]]'''\n| style=\"background:#c9c0bb;\"|No monument<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Index of Vatican City-related articles]]\n* [[Papal tombs]]\n* [[St. Peter's tomb]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{citation | last = Gardner | first = Julian | title = The Tomb and the Tiara | publisher = Clarendon Press | location = Oxford | year = 1992 | isbn = 978-0-19-817510-0 }}\n* {{citation | last =  Mann| first = H. K. | year = 2003| title =Tombs and Portraits of the Popes of the Middle Ages| publisher =Kessinger Publishing| isbn = 978-0-7661-2903-0}}\n* Reardon, Wendy J. 2004. ''The Deaths of the Popes''. Macfarland & Company, Inc. {{ISBN|978-0-7864-1527-4}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{in lang|de}} [https://web.archive.org/web/20100127105000/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/requiem/ Information and images on papal tombs (1417 and 1799)] from the Requiem project\n\n{{Vatican City topics|state=collapsed}}\n{{coord|41.9022|N|12.4533|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n[[Category:Burials at St. Peter's Basilica|Old Saint Peters]]\n[[Category:Papal tombs]]\n[[Category:History of the papacy]]\n[[Category:Sarcophagi]]\n", "name_user": "Jzsj", "label": "safe", "comment": "ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papal_tombs_in_old_St._Peter%27s_Basilica"}
{"title_page": "Antoni Ramallets", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Ramallets|Sim\u00f3n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antoni Ramallets\n| image = Antoni ramallets.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Antoni Ramallets Sim\u00f3n\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1924|7|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2013|7|30|1924|7|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Vilafranca del Pened\u00e8s]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.82}}\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = 1941\u20131942 | youthclubs1 = [[CE Europa|Europa]]\n| years1 = 1942\u20131944 | clubs1 = [[CD San Fernando|San Fernando]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 1944\u20131946 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps2 = 39 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1946\u20131962 | clubs3 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps3 = 288 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1946\u20131947 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan) | caps4 = | goals4 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1948\u20131960 | nationalteam1 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] |nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1950\u20131961 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] |nationalcaps2 = 35 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 1962\u20131963 | managerclubs1 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| manageryears2 = 1963\u20131964 | managerclubs2 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]]\n| manageryears3 = 1964 | managerclubs3 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]]\n| manageryears4 = 1965\u20131966 | managerclubs4 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| manageryears5 = 1966 | managerclubs5 = [[CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]\n| manageryears6 = 1968 | managerclubs6 = [[H\u00e9rcules CF|H\u00e9rcules]]\n| manageryears7 = 1968\u20131969 | managerclubs7 = [[Elche CF Ilicitano|Ilicitano]]\n}}\n\n'''Antoni Ramallets Sim\u00f3n''' (1 July 1924 \u2013 30 July 2013) was a Spanish [[Association football|football]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] and [[Manager (association football)manager]].\n\nHe spent most of his career at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], winning the [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]] as the best goalkeeper in [[La Liga]] on five occasions and 18 total honours.<ref>[http://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/noticias/20090713/53743727820/las-85-vidas-del-gato-con-alas.html Las 85 vidas del 'Gato con Alas' azulgrana (The 85 lives of the blaugrana 'Winged Cat')]; [[La Vanguardia]], 13 July 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref> He represented [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950 World Cup]].\n\nRamallets managed several teams in his country in the 60s, notably winning two major trophies with [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Ramallets signed for [[FC Barcelona]] in 1947 at the age of 23 from [[Real Valladolid]], where he also spent his first season after being purchased, on loan. He returned to the club to play second-fiddle to [[Juan Zambudio Velasco|Juan Velasco]], making his [[La Liga]] debut in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Sevilla FC]] on 28 November 1948. Although this was his only appearance during [[1948\u201349 La Liga|the season]] he eventually became the starter, being an essential defensive unit as his team \u2013 then named Club de F\u00fatbol Barcelona \u2013 went on to conquer six leagues and five [[Copa del Rey|domestic cups]]; in [[1951\u201352 La Liga|1951\u201352]], as they won five major trophies, he contributed with 28 league games, being awarded his first [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]].\n\nDuring the 1950s, Ramallets was a prominent member of the successful Barcelona side that also included [[Joan Segarra]], [[Mari\u00e0 Gonzalvo]], [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kubala]], [[S\u00e1ndor Kocsis]], [[Evaristo de Macedo|Evaristo]], [[Luis Su\u00e1rez (footballer, born 1935)|Luis Su\u00e1rez]] and [[Zolt\u00e1n Czibor]].<ref>[https://www.fcbarcelona.es/es/ficha/643900/1950-61-kubala-y-su-tiempo# 1950\u201361. Kubala y su tiempo (1950\u201361. Kubala and his time)]; FC Barcelona, 13 March 2018 {{in lang|es}}</ref> During his spell with the club he made 538 appearances, including 288 in the domestic league; on 6 March 1962 the ''Blaugrana'' played a [[Testimonial match|testimonial]] in his honour against [[Hamburger SV]], winning 5\u20131.<ref>[https://www.rtve.es/deportes/20130730/fallece-ramallets-mitico-portero-del-barcelona-89-anos/727721.shtml F\u00fatbol {{!}} Obituarios \u2013 Fallece Ramallets, m\u00edtico portero del Barcelona, a los 89 a\u00f1os (Football {{!}} Deaths \u2013 Death of Ramallets, legendary Barcelona goalkeeper, at the age of 89)]; [[RTVE]], 30 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[https://elpais.com/deportes/2013/07/30/actualidad/1375199929_294426.html Antoni Ramallets, el portero sin guantes que saltaba como un gato (Antoni Ramallets, the goalkeeper without gloves who jumped like a cat)]; [[El Pa\u00eds]], 30 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nRamallets coached several teams over the following decade, including old acquaintance Valladolid. In the [[1963\u201364 La Liga|1963\u201364 campaign]] he led [[Real Zaragoza]] to the fourth place in the league, the [[1963\u201364 Copa del General\u00edsimo|Spanish Cup]] and the [[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]] \u2013 a competition he had won twice as a player with Barcelona \u2013 defeating fellow league team [[Valencia CF]] in the latter.<ref>[https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/deportes/fallece-ramallets-entrenador-real-zaragoza-epoca-magnificos_872762.html Fallece Ramallets, entrenador del Real Zaragoza en la \u00e9poca de los Magn\u00edficos (Death of Ramallets, manager of Real Zaragoza during the age of the Magnificent)]; [[El Peri\u00f3dico de Arag\u00f3n]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRamallets played 35 games for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] during 11 years, making his debut against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 29 June 1950, during the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ramallets-intl.html Antonio Ramallets Sim\u00f3n \u2013 International Appearances] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708012557/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ramallets-intl.html|date=8 July 2007}}; at [[RSSSF]]</ref> During the tournament he earned the nickname ''The Cat of [[Est\u00e1dio do Maracan\u00e3|Maracan\u00e1]]'', helping the nation to the second group stage.<ref>[https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/mundial-futbol/gato-maracana-3294730 Ramallets, el gato de Maracan\u00e1 (Ramallets, the cat of Maracan\u00e1)]; [[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]], 10 June 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nRamallets also played seven games for the unofficial [[Catalonia national football team|Catalan national side]].\n\n==Death==\nRamallets died in his [[Vilafranca del Pened\u00e8s]] home near Barcelona, on 31 July 2013. He was 89 years old.<ref>[http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130730/fc-barcelona/ramallets-muerte-fallecimiento_54379004856.html Ha muerto Antoni Ramallets (Antoni Ramallets has died)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709225241/http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130730/fc-barcelona/ramallets-muerte-fallecimiento_54379004856.html|date=9 July 2015}}; [[Mundo Deportivo]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/20130730/abci-muere-ramallets-barcelona-201307301753.html Fallece a los 89 a\u00f1os Antoni Ramallets, el m\u00edtico portero del Barcelona (Antoni Ramallets, legendary Barcelona goalkeeper, dies at the age of 89)]; [[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2013/07/31/former-spain-keeper-ramallets-dies-aged-89/ Former Spain keeper Ramallets dies aged 89]; [[Euronews]], 31 July 2013</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n====Club====\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[1947\u201348 La Liga|1947\u201348]], [[1948\u201349 La Liga|1948\u201349]], [[1951\u201352 La Liga|1951\u201352]], [[1952\u201353 La Liga|1952\u201353]], [[1958\u201359 La Liga|1958\u201359]], [[1959\u201360 La Liga|1959\u201360]]\n*[[Copa del Rey|Copa del General\u00edsimo]]: [[1951 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1951]], [[1952 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1952]], [[1952\u201353 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1952\u201353]], [[1957 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1957]], [[1958\u201359 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1958\u201359]]\n*[[Copa Eva Duarte]]: 1948, 1952, 1953\n*[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: [[1955\u201358 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1955\u201358]], [[1958\u201360 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1958\u201360]]\n*[[Latin Cup]]: 1949, 1952\n\n====Individual====\n*[[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]]: 1951\u201352, 1955\u201356, 1956\u201357, 1958\u201359, 1959\u201360\n\n===Manager===\n'''Zaragoza'''\n*[[Copa del Rey|Copa del General\u00edsimo]]: [[1963\u201364 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1963\u201364]]\n*[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: [[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1963\u201364]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|8230}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|8230}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/history/detail/card/antoni-ramallets|title=FC Barcelona profile|accessdate=10 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311030244/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/history/detail/card/antoni-ramallets|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=bot: unknown}}\n*{{NFT player|id=18289}}\n*{{FIFA player|44546}}\n*[https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=17355 Spain stats at Eu-Football]\n\n{{Spain squad 1950 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{La Liga Zamora Trophy}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Antoni Ramallets \u2013 Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Real Valladolid managers}}\n{{CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s managers}}\n{{Real Zaragoza managers}}\n{{Real Murcia managers}}\n{{H\u00e9rcules CF managers}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramallets, Antoni}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Catalan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CE Europa footballers]]\n[[Category:CD San Fernando players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:1950 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Catalonia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid managers]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza managers]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia managers]]\n[[Category:CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s managers]]\n[[Category:H\u00e9rcules CF managers]]\n[[Category:Elche CF Ilicitano managers]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|Ramallets|Sim\u00f3n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Antoni Ramallets\n| image = Antoni ramallets.jpg\n| caption =\n| fullname = Antoni Ramallets Sim\u00f3n\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1924|7|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Barcelona]], Spain\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2013|7|30|1924|7|1|df=y}}\n| death_place = [[Vilafranca del Pened\u00e8s]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.82}}\n| position = [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1 = 1941\u20131942 | youthclubs1 = [[CE Europa|Europa]]\n| years1 = 1942\u20131944 | clubs1 = [[CD San Fernando|San Fernando]] | caps1 = | goals1 =\n| years2 = 1944\u20131946 | clubs2 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps2 = 39 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1946\u20131962 | clubs3 = [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] | caps3 = 288 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1946\u20131947 | clubs4 = \u2192 [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]] (loan) | caps4 = | goals4 =\n| totalcaps = | totalgoals = \n| nationalyears1 = 1948\u20131960 | nationalteam1 = [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] |nationalcaps1 = 7 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 1950\u20131961 | nationalteam2 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] |nationalcaps2 = 35 | nationalgoals2 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 1962\u20131963 | managerclubs1 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| manageryears2 = 1963\u20131964 | managerclubs2 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]]\n| manageryears3 = 1964 | managerclubs3 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]]\n| manageryears4 = 1965\u20131966 | managerclubs4 = [[Real Valladolid|Valladolid]]\n| manageryears5 = 1966 | managerclubs5 = [[CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s|Logro\u00f1\u00e9s]]\n| manageryears6 = 1968 | managerclubs6 = [[H\u00e9rcules CF|H\u00e9rcules]]\n| manageryears7 = 1968\u20131969 | managerclubs7 = [[Elche CF Ilicitano|Ilicitano]]\n}}\n\n'''Antoni Ramallets Sim\u00f3n''' (1 July 1924 \u2013 30 July 2013) was a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], and also a manager.\n\nHe spent most of his career at [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]], winning the [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy|Zamora Trophy]] as the best goalkeeper in [[La Liga]] on five occasions and 18 total honours.<ref>[http://www.lavanguardia.com/deportes/noticias/20090713/53743727820/las-85-vidas-del-gato-con-alas.html Las 85 vidas del 'Gato con Alas' azulgrana (The 85 lives of the blaugrana 'Winged Cat')]; [[La Vanguardia]], 13 July 2009 {{in lang|es}}</ref> He represented [[Spain national football team|Spain]] in the [[1950 FIFA World Cup|1950 World Cup]].\n\nRamallets managed several teams in his country in the 60s, notably winning two major trophies with [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]], Ramallets signed for [[FC Barcelona]] in 1947 at the age of 23 from [[Real Valladolid]], where he also spent his first season after being purchased, on loan. He returned to the club to play second-fiddle to [[Juan Zambudio Velasco|Juan Velasco]], making his [[La Liga]] debut in a 2\u20131 victory over [[Sevilla FC]] on 28 November 1948. Although this was his only appearance during [[1948\u201349 La Liga|the season]] he eventually became the starter, being an essential defensive unit as his team \u2013 then named Club de F\u00fatbol Barcelona \u2013 went on to conquer six leagues and five [[Copa del Rey|domestic cups]]; in [[1951\u201352 La Liga|1951\u201352]], as they won five major trophies, he contributed with 28 league games, being awarded his first [[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]].\n\nDuring the 1950s, Ramallets was a prominent member of the successful Barcelona side that also included [[Joan Segarra]], [[Mari\u00e0 Gonzalvo]], [[L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Kubala]], [[S\u00e1ndor Kocsis]], [[Evaristo de Macedo|Evaristo]], [[Luis Su\u00e1rez (footballer, born 1935)|Luis Su\u00e1rez]] and [[Zolt\u00e1n Czibor]].<ref>[https://www.fcbarcelona.es/es/ficha/643900/1950-61-kubala-y-su-tiempo# 1950\u201361. Kubala y su tiempo (1950\u201361. Kubala and his time)]; FC Barcelona, 13 March 2018 {{in lang|es}}</ref> During his spell with the club he made 538 appearances, including 288 in the domestic league; on 6 March 1962 the ''Blaugrana'' played a [[Testimonial match|testimonial]] in his honour against [[Hamburger SV]], winning 5\u20131.<ref>[https://www.rtve.es/deportes/20130730/fallece-ramallets-mitico-portero-del-barcelona-89-anos/727721.shtml F\u00fatbol {{!}} Obituarios \u2013 Fallece Ramallets, m\u00edtico portero del Barcelona, a los 89 a\u00f1os (Football {{!}} Deaths \u2013 Death of Ramallets, legendary Barcelona goalkeeper, at the age of 89)]; [[RTVE]], 30 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[https://elpais.com/deportes/2013/07/30/actualidad/1375199929_294426.html Antoni Ramallets, el portero sin guantes que saltaba como un gato (Antoni Ramallets, the goalkeeper without gloves who jumped like a cat)]; [[El Pa\u00eds]], 30 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nRamallets coached several teams over the following decade, including old acquaintance Valladolid. In the [[1963\u201364 La Liga|1963\u201364 campaign]] he led [[Real Zaragoza]] to the fourth place in the league, the [[1963\u201364 Copa del General\u00edsimo|Spanish Cup]] and the [[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]] \u2013 a competition he had won twice as a player with Barcelona \u2013 defeating fellow league team [[Valencia CF]] in the latter.<ref>[https://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/deportes/fallece-ramallets-entrenador-real-zaragoza-epoca-magnificos_872762.html Fallece Ramallets, entrenador del Real Zaragoza en la \u00e9poca de los Magn\u00edficos (Death of Ramallets, manager of Real Zaragoza during the age of the Magnificent)]; [[El Peri\u00f3dico de Arag\u00f3n]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nRamallets played 35 games for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] during 11 years, making his debut against [[Chile national football team|Chile]] on 29 June 1950, during the [[1950 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ramallets-intl.html Antonio Ramallets Sim\u00f3n \u2013 International Appearances] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708012557/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/ramallets-intl.html|date=8 July 2007}}; at [[RSSSF]]</ref> During the tournament he earned the nickname ''The Cat of [[Est\u00e1dio do Maracan\u00e3|Maracan\u00e1]]'', helping the nation to the second group stage.<ref>[https://www.sport.es/es/noticias/mundial-futbol/gato-maracana-3294730 Ramallets, el gato de Maracan\u00e1 (Ramallets, the cat of Maracan\u00e1)]; [[Sport (Spanish newspaper)|Sport]], 10 June 2014 {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n\nRamallets also played seven games for the unofficial [[Catalonia national football team|Catalan national side]].\n\n==Death==\nRamallets died in his [[Vilafranca del Pened\u00e8s]] home near Barcelona, on 31 July 2013. He was 89 years old.<ref>[http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130730/fc-barcelona/ramallets-muerte-fallecimiento_54379004856.html Ha muerto Antoni Ramallets (Antoni Ramallets has died)] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150709225241/http://www.mundodeportivo.com/20130730/fc-barcelona/ramallets-muerte-fallecimiento_54379004856.html|date=9 July 2015}}; [[Mundo Deportivo]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/20130730/abci-muere-ramallets-barcelona-201307301753.html Fallece a los 89 a\u00f1os Antoni Ramallets, el m\u00edtico portero del Barcelona (Antoni Ramallets, legendary Barcelona goalkeeper, dies at the age of 89)]; [[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]], 31 July 2013 {{in lang|es}}</ref><ref>[http://www.euronews.com/2013/07/31/former-spain-keeper-ramallets-dies-aged-89/ Former Spain keeper Ramallets dies aged 89]; [[Euronews]], 31 July 2013</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n====Club====\n'''Barcelona'''\n*[[La Liga]]: [[1947\u201348 La Liga|1947\u201348]], [[1948\u201349 La Liga|1948\u201349]], [[1951\u201352 La Liga|1951\u201352]], [[1952\u201353 La Liga|1952\u201353]], [[1958\u201359 La Liga|1958\u201359]], [[1959\u201360 La Liga|1959\u201360]]\n*[[Copa del Rey|Copa del General\u00edsimo]]: [[1951 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1951]], [[1952 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1952]], [[1952\u201353 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1952\u201353]], [[1957 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1957]], [[1958\u201359 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1958\u201359]]\n*[[Copa Eva Duarte]]: 1948, 1952, 1953\n*[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: [[1955\u201358 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1955\u201358]], [[1958\u201360 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1958\u201360]]\n*[[Latin Cup]]: 1949, 1952\n\n====Individual====\n*[[Ricardo Zamora Trophy]]: 1951\u201352, 1955\u201356, 1956\u201357, 1958\u201359, 1959\u201360\n\n===Manager===\n'''Zaragoza'''\n*[[Copa del Rey|Copa del General\u00edsimo]]: [[1963\u201364 Copa del General\u00edsimo|1963\u201364]]\n*[[Inter-Cities Fairs Cup]]: [[1963\u201364 Inter-Cities Fairs Cup|1963\u201364]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|8230}}\n*{{BDFutbol manager|8230}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/history/detail/card/antoni-ramallets|title=FC Barcelona profile|accessdate=10 March 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311030244/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/club/history/detail/card/antoni-ramallets|archive-date=11 March 2016|url-status=bot: unknown}}\n*{{NFT player|id=18289}}\n*{{FIFA player|44546}}\n*[https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=17355 Spain stats at Eu-Football]\n\n{{Spain squad 1950 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{La Liga Zamora Trophy}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Antoni Ramallets \u2013 Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{Real Valladolid managers}}\n{{CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s managers}}\n{{Real Zaragoza managers}}\n{{Real Murcia managers}}\n{{H\u00e9rcules CF managers}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ramallets, Antoni}}\n[[Category:1924 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Barcelona]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Catalan footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:CE Europa footballers]]\n[[Category:CD San Fernando players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid players]]\n[[Category:FC Barcelona players]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:1950 FIFA World Cup players]]\n[[Category:Catalonia international footballers]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Real Valladolid managers]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza managers]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia managers]]\n[[Category:CD Logro\u00f1\u00e9s managers]]\n[[Category:H\u00e9rcules CF managers]]\n[[Category:Elche CF Ilicitano managers]]\n[[Category:Association football players who received a testimonial]]\n", "name_user": "Quite A Character", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor intro tweak, done!", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Antoni_Ramallets"}
{"title_page": "Peter Knights", "text_new": "{{short description|Australian rules footballer, born 1946}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox AFL biography\n| name = Peter Knights\n| image = PeterKnights(250).webp\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1952|3|30|df=y}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| originalteam = Longwarry\n| debutdate = Round 9, 1969\n| debutteam = [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n| debutopponent = [[St Kilda Football Club|St Kilda]]\n| debutstadium = [[Moorabbin Oval|Moorabbin]]\n| height = 188 cm\n| weight = 84 kg\n| position = \n| statsend = 1985\n| years1 = 1969\u20131985\n| club1 = [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n| games_goals1 = 264 (201)\n| coachyears1 = 1987\u20131989\n| coachclub1 = [[Brisbane Bears]]\n| coachgames_wins1 = {{0}}59 (16\u201343\u20130)\n| coachyears2 = 1994\u20131995\n| coachclub2 = [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]]\n| coachgames_wins2 = {{0}}45 (20\u201325\u20130)\n| coachgames_winstotal = 104 (36\u201368\u20130)\n| careerhighlights = * 3\u00d7 [[List of Australian Football League premiers|VFL premiership player]] ([[1976 VFL Grand Final|1976]], [[1978 VFL Grand Final|1978]], [[1983 VFL Grand Final|1983]])\n* [[List of Hawthorn Football Club leading goalkickers|Hawthorn leading goalkicker]] ([[1972 VFL season|1972]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[Peter Crimmins Medal|Peter Crimmins Perpetual Memorial Trophy]] ([[1975 VFL season|1975]], [[1978 VFL season|1978]])\n* [[Australian Football Hall of Fame]]\n* [[Hawthorn Football Club#Team of the Century|Hawthorn Team of the Century]]\n* [[Hawthorn Football Club|Hawthorn]] Hall of Fame \u2013 Legend status\n| fullname = \n}}\n'''Peter Knights''' (born 30 March 1952) is a former [[Australian rules football]]er and coach who represented {{AFL Haw}} in the [[Victorian Football League (1897\u20131989)|Victorian Football League]] (VFL). Widely regarded as one of Australian football's finest centre half-backs, despite suffering numerous injuries, Knights was recognized for his contribution to the game when he was among the inaugural inductees into the [[Australian Football Hall of Fame]] in 1996<ref>[http://www.afl.com.au/players/tabid/856/default.aspx Players in the Australian Football Hall of Fame]</ref> and later in the Hawthorn Team of the Century.<ref>[http://www.hawthornfc.com.au/team%20of%20the%20century/tabid/4819/default.aspx Hawthorn Team of the Century] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110223123516/http://www.hawthornfc.com.au/team%20of%20the%20century/tabid/4819/default.aspx |date=23 February 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Playing career ==\nKnights was raised on a dairy farm in [[Longwarry]], where he played for the local football club and attended school in neighbouring [[Drouin, Victoria|Drouin]].<ref name=\"knightsfarewell\">{{cite news|first=Hannah|last=Driscoll|url=http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/sport/country-football/hawthorn-legend-peter-knights-prepares-for-vic-country-final-farewell/news-story/3d93377b409bd146e4c143889699853d|title=Hawthorn legend Peter Knights prepares for Vic Country final farewell|publisher=The Weekly Times|date=8 July 2016}}</ref> In his first two seasons at {{AFL Haw}}, Knights would get a taxi to training, then on the weekends would be driven to games by his parents. To make it easier for him to play without having to make long commutes to and from home, Knights was billeted with a family in Melbourne and finished his education at [[Camberwell High School]].<ref name=\"knightsfarewell\"/> He was in his own words a \"quiet and shy\" country kid when he arrived at Hawthorn, and it would be champion rover [[Peter Crimmins]] who helped Knights settle in at the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawthornfc.com.au/news/2016-10-07/crimmos-cup|date=7 October 2016|title=Crimmo's Cup - The story behind the Hawks' 1976 triumph and the famous photo|publisher=hawthornfc.com.au|first=Ashley|last=Browne}}</ref> He became easily identifiable on the field with his blond hair and his ability to frequently take spectacular high [[Mark (Australian football)|marks]]. He was also a great exponent of the drop kick and the torpedo punt kick.\n\nAfter playing only five games in his debut season, Knights established himself in the first team in 1970. The following year he did so well in that position that he was chosen for Victoria, winning the Simpson Medal for the best on ground in the match against [[Western Australia Australian rules football team|Western Australia]] in Perth. However, he missed out on Hawthorn's [[1971 VFL Grand Final|1971 premiership]] success due to a knee injury.\n\nKnights was moved briefly to full-forward in 1972 after a serious knee injury to [[Peter Hudson]] forced Hawthorn to experiment in the position before finally settling on [[Michael Moncrieff]]. He actually finished as Hawthorn's leading goal-kicking with 46 goals, but was moved back to defence before the season was over. After injury problems restricted his 1973 season, for the next three years Knights was rated the best centre half-back in the game. In 1975, Knights finally had the chance to participate in the first of four Grand Finals. [[North Melbourne Football Club|North Melbourne]] were too good on the day, winning their first-ever Premiership. Knights was Hawthorn's best player on the day, and capped off a fine personal year by winning the club Best and Fairest award.\n\nKnights' stellar form continued into 1976 before he suffered a broken [[collarbone]] early in the match against {{AFL Foo}} in Round 14, which ruled him out for the next seven matches.<ref>{{cite web|first=Richard|last=Allsop|title=Footy Flashbacks: Round 14|date=22 June 2016|publisher=hawthornfc.com.au|url=http://www.hawthornfc.com.au/news/2016-06-22/footy-flashbacks-round-14}}</ref> Despite this, Knights still managed to come second in the [[1976 Brownlow Medal]] count, polling an astonishing 45 votes to finish three votes behind Essendon's [[Graham Moss]]. He shrugged off that disappointment to be one of Hawthorn's best players in the [[1976 VFL Grand Final]] triumph, later joining some of his teammates at [[Peter Crimmins]]' bedside.\n\nFrom 1977 onwards Knights was frequently rested up forward to reduce the risk of injuries, but still did enough great work at centre half-back to finish one vote behind [[Malcolm Blight]] in the [[1978 Brownlow Medal]] count. He would shrug off the disappointment of finishing runner-up in the Brownlow by starring in the [[1978 VFL Grand Final]]. After being knocked out while playing in defence, Knights was moved forward in the last quarter, where he took a series of fine marks and kicked two goals to help secure Hawthorn's fourth Premiership. During his stellar 1978 season Knights also claimed his second Simpson Medal with a dominant display for Victoria against WA in Perth.\n\nThe litany of injuries that Knights had suffered through his career began to catch up with him, and from 1979 to 1981, he played in only 26 out of a possible 66 games. Amid rumours of retirement, Knights rebounded to play impressive football in his final years. In 1983, he booted six goals in the Qualifying Final to guide Hawthorn to a thrilling four-point win against [[Fitzroy Lions|Fitzroy]], and was again among the best players on the field as the Hawks crushed {{AFL Ess}} in the [[1983 VFL Grand Final|Grand Final]]. \nKnights reached the 250-game milestone the following season against {{AFL StK}}, gathering 23 possessions and kicking two goals,<ref>{{cite web|title=The best 250th in Hawthorn history?|date=30 May 2016|url=http://www.hawthornfc.com.au/news/2016-05-30/the-best-250th-in-hawthorn-history|publisher=hawthornfc.com.au}}</ref> but a knee injury restricted him to just three further games. In 1985, Knights showed traces of brilliant form \u2013 kicking nine goals against {{AFL Car}} in Round 10. The Preliminary Final against {{AFL Foo}} would turn out to be his final VFL game. He had just four disposals, and was dropped for the Grand Final, a surprising decision for some people, given his reputation as a performer on the VFL's biggest stage. Yet again, Knights would bounce back from the disappointment to finish his career in a semblance of style, kicking a bag of goals to help Hawthorn defeat Carlton in the reserves Grand Final.\n\n== Coaching career ==\nAlthough Knights enjoyed spectacular success on the field, it was a different story as a coach. However, it should also be remembered that he was in charge of teams that were either relatively new and inexperienced (Brisbane), or undergoing restructuring (Hawthorn).\n\nIn 1986, the VFL decided to expand and include one team each from [[Western Australia]] and [[Queensland]]. The [[Brisbane Bears]], based on the [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]] in [[South East Queensland]], recruited Knights as their inaugural coach, despite his lack of coaching experience. The club won their first game, and although expectations of the new side were low, it was considered a significant achievement that the team was able to avoid finishing last in their first season.\n\nDespite this, the Bears' results in 1988 and 1989 failed to improve, with the club suffering regular thrashings. Besides the substandard quality of the training and playing facilities, lack of assistance from the VFL, and squad disharmony, Knights also had limited control over team selection; part way through the [[1988 VFL season]], he wanted star signing [[Warwick Capper]] dropped from the senior team due to poor form, but was overruled by club president [[Paul Cronin]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Jon|last=Pierik|publisher=The Age|date=6 May 2014|title=Warwick Capper's life with bad-news Bears|url=http://www.theage.com.au/afl/afl-news/warwick-cappers-life-with-badnews-bears-20140506-zr5hn.html}}</ref> Knights was dismissed as coach with seven games remaining in the 1989 season<ref>[https://news.google.com.au/newspapers?id=hJsQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=aZEDAAAAIBAJ&dq=peter-knights%20sacked&pg=6691%2C6848905 Shock and tears at golden boy's demise]</ref> and replaced with team [[psychologist]], [[Paul Feltham]]. Knights was considered to have been unlucky, as ineffective club management and poor relationships amongst his underperforming players seen as major contributing factors in the club's performance.\n\nAfter a brief coaching stint at Tasmanian club [[Devonport Football Club|Devonport]] from 1990 to 1993,<ref>http://www.devonportfc.com.au/history/listOnePositionType?positiontype=Senior%20Coach</ref> Knights returned to Hawthorn as senior coach for the 1994 AFL season. He managed to lead the team into the finals series, but were knocked out by {{AFL NM}} in the first final. The following year the team finished second last, however, and Knights was again sacked.\n\nIn 2009, Knights was appointed senior representative coach of the [[Victorian Country Football League]] and held the position until 2016.<ref>{{cite news|title=Hawthorn great Peter Knights to call it a day|date=29 April 2016|first=Hannah|last=Driscoll|publisher=The Weekly Times|url=http://www.weeklytimesnow.com.au/sport/country-football/hawthorn-great-peter-knights-to-call-it-a-day/news-story/6215bc33e92cd6766ea78986ff3af82d}}</ref>\n\n==Statistics==\n: ''Statistics are correct to the end of the 2016 season''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afltables.com/afl/stats/players/P/Peter_Knights.html|title=Peter Knights \u2013 Stats|publisher=AFL Tables|accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n{{AFL player statistics legend}}\n{{AFL player statistics start}}\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1969 VFL season|1969]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 5 || 3 || 1 || 34 || 9 || 43 || 10 || - || 0.6 || 0.2 || 6.8 || 1.8 || 8.6 || 2.0 || -\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1970 VFL season|1970]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 18 || 5 || 0 || 265 || 28 || 293 || 84 || - || 0.3 || 0.0 || 14.7 || 1.6 || 16.3 || 4.7 || -\n|- style=\