| 8 || 1 || 2 || 91 || 39 || 130 || 47 || - || 0.1 || 0.3 || 11.4 || 4.9 || 16.3 || 5.9 || -\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1982 VFL season|1982]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 14 || 14 || 18 || 141 || 52 || 193 || 54 || - || 1.0 || 1.3 || 10.1 || 3.7 || 13.8 || 3.9 || -\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1983 VFL season|1983]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 21 || 38 || 29 || 279 || 108 || 387 || 144 || - || 1.8 || 1.4 || 13.3 || 5.1 || 18.4 || 6.9 || -\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1984 VFL season|1984]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 4 || 5 || 3 || 33 || 13 || 46 || 21 || - || 1.3 || 0.8 || 8.3 || 3.3 || 11.5 || 5.3 || -\n|- style=\"background-color: #EAEAEA\"\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" | [[1985 VFL season|1985]]\n|{{AFL Haw}}\n| 24 || 13 || 37 || 19 || 121 || 23 || 144 || 75 || - || 2.8 || 1.5 || 9.3 || 1.8 || 11.1 || 5.8 || -\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! colspan=3| Career\n! 264\n! 201\n! 138\n! 3356\n! 719\n! 4075\n! 1348\n! -\n! 0.8\n! 0.5\n! 12.7\n! 2.7\n! 15.4\n! 5.1\n! -\n|}\n\n== Personal life ==\nKnights had a son, Benjamin, in 1978 with his first wife Julie. He divorced and remarried Angela, a schoolteacher, and had two daughters, Sarah (born 1993) and Rebecca. In February 2015, Knights publicly revealed that Sarah had been struggling with a mystery illness that left her confined to a wheelchair.<ref name=\"sarahillness\">{{cite news|title=Peter Knights wants to find cure for daughter Sarah's illness|work=Herald Sun|date=5 February 2015|first=Rita|last=Panahi|authorlink=Rita Panahi|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/peter-knights-wants-to-find-cure-for-daughter-sarahs-illness/news-story/de3409fb43c1e0ea2d635cd66ad0b1be}}</ref> Sarah and her mother flew to Germany for specialist treatment, where a diagnosis of [[Lyme disease]] was confirmed.<ref name=\"sarahillness\"/><ref name=\"sarahreturn\">{{cite news|title=Sarah Knights takes first steps after being told she might never walk|publisher=Herald Sun|date=23 October 2015|first=Rita|last=Panahi|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/news/victoria/sarah-knights-takes-first-steps-after-being-told-she-might-never-walk/news-story/f72c8ad41f85596b33393f6ad181178e}}</ref> They returned to Melbourne later in the year to commence intensive rehabilitation.<ref name=\"sarahreturn\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{AFL Tables|ref=P/Peter_Knights.html}}\n* {{AustralianFootball|ref=peter%2Bknights/10230}}\n* [http://www.hawkheadquarters.com/player.aspx?playerid=594&view=default Profile at Hawk Headquarters]\n\n{{1976/78 Hawthorn dual premiership players}}\n{{1983 Hawthorn premiership players}}\n{{Simpson Medal winners}}\n{{1983 Victoria State of Origin players}}\n{{1988 Queensland Australian Rules Football State of Origin Players}}\n{{Inaugural Brisbane Bears team}}\n{{Brisbane Bears coaches}}\n{{Hawthorn Football Club coaches}}\n{{Hawthorn Team of The Century}}\n{{Peter Crimmins Medal}}\n{{Hawthorn leading goalkickers}}\n{{Alex Jesaulenko Medal}}\n{{Australian Football Media Association Player of the Year}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Knights, Peter}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Australian rules footballers from Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Peter Crimmins Medal winners]]\n[[Category:Hawthorn Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Hawthorn Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Brisbane Bears coaches]]\n[[Category:Australian Football Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Devonport Football Club coaches]]\n[[Category:Victorian State of Origin players]]\n", "name_user": "Jordandaniel72", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added image of Peter Knights", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Knights"}
{"title_page": "Solomon (name)", "text_new": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Solomon\n| image= File:King-Solomon-Russian-icon.jpg\n| imagesize=\n| caption= [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian]] [[icon]] of King Solomon.\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u0252|l|\u0259|m|\u0259n}}\n| gender = Male\n| meaning = \"Man of Peace\"\n| origin = Hebrew\n| alternative spelling = Salomon\n| related names = [[Suleiman]], [[Sulayman]], [[Salom\u00e3o (given name)|Salom\u00e3o]], Shlomo, Soghomon, [[Salman (name)|Salman]], [[Zalman (name)|Zalman]]\n| footnotes =  \n| wikt = \n}}\n'''Solomon''' is a common given name and surname derived from [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] {{lang|arc|\u072b\u0720\u071d\u0721\u0718\u0722\u200e}} ''\u0160leimon''; '''Sol''' as a given name is usually a form of \"Solomon\". Its Hebrew form, '''Shlomo''' is related to the word ''[[shalom]]'' (\"peace\");<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Kaplan\n | first = Aryeh\n | title = The Bahir\n | publisher = Weiser Books\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bahironeofo00nehu\n | url-access = registration\n | quote = solomon shalom peace.\n | year = 1989\n | isbn = 0-87728-618-3\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bahironeofo00nehu/page/130 130]\n }}</ref> and is often chosen in part as a reference to the well-known King [[Solomon]] mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]]. (The [[Arabic language|Arabic]] name \u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646, '''[[Sulaiman]]''' or '''Sulayman''', also meaning \"peace\", is regarded as equivalent to Solomon, and [[Solomon in Islam|the Islamic prophet Suleiman]] and King Solomon are generally regarded as accounts of the same person.)\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Single name==\n*   Solomon (\u03a3\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd), ancient Koine Greek name, derived from 3rd cent. B.C.E. Septuagint translation of the Hebrew name \u05e9\u05b0\u05c1\u05dc\u05b9\u05de\u05b9\u05d4 (Shelomoh). \n* [[Solomon (Byzantine general)]], 6th-century Byzantine eunuch general, governor of Africa\n* [[Solomon the Eunuch]], associate of Byzantine general Belisarius\n* [[Solomon of Hungary]]\n* [[Solomon I of Imereti]]\n* [[Solomon II of Imereti]]\n* [[Solomon of Montpellier]], a 13th-century Rabbi\n* [[Solomon (pianist)]], the professional name of the British pianist Solomon Cutner\n* [[Solomon (rapper)]] (born 1991) American electronic hip-pop recording artist\n\n==Given name==\n* [[Solomon Brannan]], American football player\n* [[Solomon Busendich]] (born 1984) Kenyan long-distance runner\n* [[Solomon Burke]] (1940\u20132010) American recording artist\n* [[Solomon Elimimian]] (born 1986), American football player\n* [[Solomon Ferris]] (c.1748-1803), British naval officer\n* [[Solomon kaDinuzulu]] (1891\u20131933) king of the Zulu nation from 1913 until 1933\n* [[Sol Lesser]], film producer\n* [[Solomon Luna]] (1858-1912), American rancher and banker.\n* [[Solomon Machover]] (1906-1976), American psychologist\n* [[Solomon Northup]] (1808-c.1863), free black man kidnapped into slavery\n* [[Sol Rosenberg]], businessman and Dachau concentration camp survivor\n* [[Sol Stern]], senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute\n* [[Solomon Sufrin]] (1881\u20131931), New York assemblyman\n* [[Solomon Thomas]] (born 1995), American football player\n* [[Solomon Trujillo]] (born 1951) American businessman\n* [[Sol Wachtler]], former Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals\n\n==Surname==\n*[[Abraham Solomon]], British painter\n*[[Albert Solomon]] (1876\u20131914), Australian politician, premier of Tasmania\n*[[Anthony M. Solomon]] (1919\u20132008), American Treasury undersecretary and president of the Federal Reserve Board of New York\n*[[Anu Solomon]] (born 1996), American football player\n*[[Barbara Probst Solomon]] (1928\u20132019), American author and journalist\n*[[Charles J. Solomon]] (1906\u20131975), American bridge player\n*[[Clinton Solomon]] (born 1983), American football player\n*[[David Solomon (disambiguation)]], several people\n*[[Dean Solomon]], Australian footballer\n*[[Duane Solomon]] American middle distance runner\n*[[Edward I. Solomon]] (born 1946), Stanford University chemistry professor\n*[[Emanuel Solomon]] (1800\u20131875) pioneer of South Australia\n*Francis Darwin Solomon (1937\u20131998), American actor, professionally known as [[Darwin Joston]]\n*[[Freddie Solomon]], American football player\n*[[George Solomon]], American sportswriter\n*[[Gerald B. H. Solomon]] (1930\u20132001), American politician\n*[[Glenn Solomon]] American physicist\n*[[Grant Solomon]] (born 1995), American tennis player\n*[[Gustave Solomon]] (1930\u20131996), American mathematician and engineer\n*[[Harold Solomon]] (born 1952), American tennis player\n*[[Haym Solomon]] (1740\u20131785), financier of the U.S. in the Revolutionary War\n*[[Ikey Solomon]] (1785\u20131850), English criminal\n*[[Jacques Solomon]] (1908\u20131942), French physicist and Marxist\n*[[Jesse Solomon]], American football player\n*[[Joe Solomon]], West Indian cricketer\n*[[John R. Solomon]] (1910\u20131985), Canadian politician\n*[[Josh Solomon]], guitar player and lead singer of the band Josh and the Empty Pockets\n*Kimberley Solomon, birth name of [[Kimberly Quinn]] (born 1961), American journalist, commentator, and magazine publisher\n*[[Lawrence Solomon]], columnist\n*[[Linda Solomon]], music critic\n*[[Manor Solomon]] (born 1999), Israeli football player\n*[[Martin K. Solomon]], mathematician\n*[[Martin M. Solomon]] (born 1950), American politician, New York state senator and Supreme Court judge\n*[[Maynard Solomon]], American psychologist, music producer, and writer\n*[[Morris Solomon, Jr.]], serial killer\n*[[Mose Solomon]] (1900\u20131966), rabbi and baseball player\n*[[Norman Solomon]], author and media critic\n*[[Peggy Solomon]] (1909\u20131995), American bridge player\n*[[Richard Solomon (disambiguation)]], several people\n*[[Robert Solomon (disambiguation)]], several people\n*[[Rosalind Fox Solomon]] (born 1930), American photographer\n*[[Russ Solomon]], founder of Tower Records\n*[[Samuel Moss Solomon]] (1769\u20131842), early settler in Australia, many notable descendants\n*[[Shalonda Solomon]] American sprinter\n*[[Sheldon Solomon]], co-developer of terror management theory\n*[[Shirley Solomon]], Canadian television talk show host\n*[[Simeon Solomon]], British Pre-Raphaelite painter\n*[[Solomon Joseph Solomon]], British Pre-Raphaelite painter\n*[[Stacey Solomon]] (born 1989) British singer, television presenter, and model\n*[[Steven Solomon]] (born 1993), Australian Olympic sprinter\n*[[Suniti Solomon]] (1938 or 1939\u20132015), Indian physician and microbiologist\n*[[Susan Solomon]] (born 1956), atmospheric chemist, MIT faculty\n*[[Vaiben Louis Solomon]] (1853\u20131908) first mayor of Darwin and 21st premier of South Australia\n*[[Vonzell Solomon]], American singer\n*[[Willie Solomon]], basketball player\n\n==Fictional characters==\n* [[Dick Solomon]], lead character of the television sitcom '3rd Rock from the Sun'\n* [[Sally Solomon]], character in the television sitcom '3rd Rock from the Sun'\n*[[Solomon Kane]], lead character in some of Robert E. Howard short stories.\ufffc\n* [[Harry Solomon]], character in the television sitcom '3rd Rock from the Sun'\n* [[Tommy Solomon (3rd Rock from the Sun)|Tommy Solomon]], character in the television sitcom '3rd Rock from the Sun'\n* Peter Solomon, character in Dan Brown's ''[[The Lost Symbol]]''\n* Katherine Solomon, character in Dan Brown's ''The Lost Symbol''\n* [[Solomon Grundy (comics)|Solomon Grundy]], villain character from DC Comics comic books and TV series\n\n==See also==\n* [[Solomon (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Solomons (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Salman (name)|Salman]]\n* [[Sol (given name)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name|type=both}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Solomon\n| image= File:King-Solomon-Russian-icon.jpg\n| imagesize=\n| caption= [[Russian Orthodox Church|Russian]] [[icon]] of King Solomon.\n| pronunciation= {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|\u0252|l|\u0259|m|\u0259n}}\n| gender = Male\n| meaning = \"Man of Peace\"\n| origin = Hebrew\n| alternative spelling = Salomon\n| related names = [[Suleiman]], [[Sulayman]], [[Salom\u00e3o (given name)|Salom\u00e3o]], Shlomo, Soghomon, [[Salman (name)|Salman]], [[Zalman (name)|Zalman]]\n| footnotes =  \n| wikt = \n}}\n'''Solomon''' is a common given name and surname derived from [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] {{lang|arc|\u072b\u0720\u071d\u0721\u0718\u0722\u200e}} ''\u0160leimon''; '''Sol''' as a given name is usually a form of \"Solomon\". Its Hebrew form, '''Shlomo''' is related to the word ''[[shalom]]'' (\"peace\");<ref>{{cite book\n | last = Kaplan\n | first = Aryeh\n | title = The Bahir\n | publisher = Weiser Books\n | url = https://archive.org/details/bahironeofo00nehu\n | url-access = registration\n | quote = solomon shalom peace.\n | year = 1989\n | isbn = 0-87728-618-3\n | page = [https://archive.org/details/bahironeofo00nehu/page/130 130]\n }}</ref> and is often chosen in part as a reference to the well-known King [[Solomon]] mentioned in the [[Hebrew Bible]]. (The [[Arabic language|Arabic]] name \u0633\u0644\u064a\u0645\u0627\u0646, '''[[Sulaiman]]''' or '''Sulayman''', also meaning \"peace\", is regarded as equivalent to Solomon, and [[Solomon in Islam|the Islamic prophet Suleiman]] and King Solomon are generally regarded as accounts of the same person.)\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Single name==\n*   Solomon (\u03a3\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03bc\u03ce\u03bd), ancient Koine Greek name, derived from 3rd cent. B.C.E. Septuagint translation of the Hebrew name \u05e9\u05b0\u05c1\u05dc\u05b9\u05de\u05b9\u05d4 (Shelomoh). \n* [[Solomon (Byzantine general)]], 6th-century Byzantine eunuch general, governor of Africa\n* [[Solomon the Eunuch]], associate of Byzantine general Belisarius\n* [[Solomon of Hungary]]\n* [[Solomon I of Imereti]]\n* [[Solomon II of Imereti]]\n* [[Solomon of Montpellier]], a 13th-century Rabbi\n* [[Solomon (pianist)]], the professional name of the British pianist Solomon Cutner\n* [[Solomon (rapper)]] (born 1991) American electronic hip-pop recording artist\n\n==Given name==\n* [[Solomon Brannan]], American football player\n* [[Solomon Busendich]] (born 1984) Kenyan long-distance runner\n* [[Solomon Burke]] (1940\u20132010) American recording artist\n* [[Solomon Elimimian]] (born 1986), American football player\n* [[Solomon Ferris]] (c.1748-1803), British naval officer\n* [[Solomon kaDinuzulu]] (1891\u20131933) king of the Zulu nation from 1913 until 1933\n* [[Sol Lesser]], film producer\n* [[Solomon Luna]] (1858-1912), American rancher and banker.\n* [[Solomon Machover]] (1906-1976), American psychologist\n* [[Solomon Northup]] (1808-c.1863), free black man kidnapped into slavery\n* [[Sol Rosenberg]], businessman and Dachau concentration camp survivor\n* [[Sol Stern]], senior fellow at the Manhattan Institute\n* [[Solomon Sufrin]] (1881\u20131931), New York assemblyman\n* [[Solomon Thomas]] (born 1995), American football player\n* [[Solomon Trujillo]] (born 1951) American businessman\n* [[Sol Wachtler]], former Chief Judge of the New York Court of Appeals\n\n==Surname==\n*[[Abraham Solomon]], British painter\n*[[Albert Solomon]] (1876\u20131914), Australian politician, premier of Tasmania\n*[[Anthony M. Solomon]] (1919\u20132008), American Treasury undersecretary and president of the Federal Reserve Board of New York\n*[[Anu Solomon]] (born 1996), American football player\n*[[Barbara Probst Solomon]] (1928\u20132019), American author and journalist\n*[[Charles J. Solomon]] (1906\u20131975), American bridge player\n*[[Clinton Solomon]] (born 1983), American football player\n*[[David Solomon (disambiguation)]], several people\n*[[Dean Solomon]], Australian footballer\n*[[Duane Solomon]] American middle distance runner\n*[[Edward I. Solomon]] (born 1946), Stanford University chemistry professor\n*[[Emanuel Solomon]] (1800\u20131875) pioneer of South Australia\n*Francis Darwin Solomon (1937\u20131998), American acto